description.text: I made this as a challenge for myself, it's the first rendition of a scale model of a full flow methane oxygen rocket engine that I conceived myself. I used pre existing engines as guides to build it, it's largely grounded in the SSME and BE-4 engines. The model has a fully built interior with modelled turbopumps and injector systems (I can upload the various components if there is an interest in them, although I should mention there are over 500 individual components but I could upload the main ones and the primary sub assemblies if it's requested). One of the reasons I started this project was because I felt that it would be an incredible idea to have a model rocket motor in the reach of any student interested in aeronautical engineering. There's a thread that I put up about the engine here: http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=39200.msg1468297#msg1468297 There's also a lot of the designs as sheets there as well, which is helpful to demonstrate the inner workings of the engine.

Printer:

M3D

Notes: I suggest rotating the model so that the nozzle is always orientated downward (Larger end on the ground) as it will use less scaffolding etc.
If printed as two halves you can glue it together.

I spent a couple months studying engines, I have put together a notebook of many of the processes and mechanics of how the engine works. 
After I had studied the engine I began painstakingly modelling the components in CAD, and then began assembling the engine. 
I'm quite satisfied with the result but I am currently planning the next version of the engine in an attempt to improve it.

How it works: The Pachacuti engine is the prototype bipropellant (two propellants) engine model that I've been designing. It uses cryogenically frozen fuel (i.e. fuel kept at extremely cold temperatures so that it is a liquid, the oxygen must be kept below -218 degrees celsius and the methane below -182 degrees celsius). The engine is a full flow staged combustion cycle, both propellants are sent through two prebuners and are partially burned using a smaller fraction of the opposite propellant. This results in an oxidiser-rich gas and a fuel-rich gas. The resultant hot gases are sent though a turbine which drives a shaft connected to two more turbines (impellers) in what are called the centrifugal turbopumps which increase the fuel pressure. These two turbopumps are what drive the fuel into the preburners and engine. The fuel turbopump is driven by the fuel-rich preburner, while the oxidiser-rich preburner drives the oxidiser turbopump. After the hot gases have driven the turbine they are sent into the main combustion chamber, whereupon they are ignited together and fully combusted and ejected into the nozzle. The nozzle's shape then forces the resultant exhaust gases out in a supersonic flow which results a huge amount of thrust. The nozzle, therefore gets very hot very quickly, as the heat has nowhere to dissipate into. If this were left alone, the nozzle itself would melt. That is why, the entirety of the inside of the nozzle is covered over in a set of capillary tubes. These four helical structures carry cold liquid methane directly from the turbopumps both cooling the nozzle dramatically and also allowing the methane to quickly expand, sending it at an even higher pressure to the preburners.

title: Spacer Bracket for a 1U Power Supply

description.text:
My friend Brian gives away a do-it-yourself NAS machine every year.  We weren't all that pleased with the way his 1U PSU fit in the U-NAS NSC-800 case.  It would be just fine around the house, but we weren't happy that it would be flopping around during shipping.
I designed a quick bracket to keep the power supply from moving vertically, so it ought to survive shipping now!
This is a customizable part, so you should be able to make it fit other situations.
For another project involving the UNAS case, Brian needed fit a pair of SSDs and a fairly large 10 gigabit Ethernet card.  The UNAS SSD brackets didn't leave much room for that, so I added a pair of mounts to our existing PSU spacer bracket.  
The model with the SSD mounts is slightly different than what we actually used in Brian's case.  I eliminated most of the unnecessary support between the two SSD mounts, so you should be able to spin it around 180 degrees, if you'd prefer.

description.text: This is a small bracket you can snap a standard Apple-brand USB charger into. Add it to existing enclosures for things you might need to power by USB, like this nightlight I designed for example. Now you have an appliance you can power and attach to the wall in any home in North America (or Japan). Ideas include: a Raspberry Pi Zero, an Arduino, an ESP8266 type chip, pretty much anything that you can run on 5v/1amp. The world's your oyster, etc. It was hard to find a balance between keeping the plug secure, and not putting too much stress on the PLA when you snap it in. I found the best solution was to keep it a bit looser for durability, but add a notch so that you could use a ny-tie to really secure things if your project demanded it. I designed this in Blender, using lots of modifiers, so if you wish to modify this general idea to fit whatever USB power supply you prefer it should be pretty easy. title: Fortis Tricopter GoPro, Low Profile Reinforced Zip Tie Mount

description.text:
This is for anyone who wants to 3D print well fitting GoPro mounts onto their Fortis Air Frames Tricopter so that they can use their GoPro housing for extra protection. This GoPro mount requires you glue a nut onto the side or tighten the GoPro screw with a nut. A nylon nut would work well for this. You can get a set of 4 nylon locking nuts in size M5 (size for GoPro) at nearly any hardware store for around 2-3 USD, and you would never have to worry about the bolts coming loose or the camera moving in flight/crashes. However a non-locking nut seems to work just as well once you tighten it onto the PLA. There are two designs here one with the word FRONT on the front side, one without it. The mount only mounts in one direction but allows for small zip ties to fit through the camera mounting holes and to be able to solidly lock the mount in place. 
Made with PLA 230C, 2 shell, 20% infill (25% works nearly just as well, 20% doesn't take as long and is slightly more flexible which you'll probably want for this).

title: C270 Webcam mount for FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text: Logitech C270 mount for the FlashForge Creator Pro and similar printers (only tested on FFCP). I really liked this design because I wanted my camera to be positioned as if I were actually watching it plus someone already made a part for it to be detachable, so I modified the design to work for the C270. The beam portions of my design I used 1/2" Pex pipe (.625" OD) along with a 90° elbow. That way all I needed to actually model was the end cap adapters for the Pex pipe. The actual part that attaches to the C270 is located here. This part is great because it allows you to adjust the C270 vertically and horizontally. That part relies on this design to mount on so I based my Pex end cap design off of that. If you're confused on what you need for this frankenstein design look below.

• 1 x Hanger
  • 1 x Pex Base
  • 1 x Pex End
  • 1 x C270 Mount

• 1 x 1/2" Pex pipe (The horizontal and vertical Pex pipe lengths I used are 4.75" and 2" respectively, but the great part about this design is you can cut it to your own desired lengths.)
  • 1 x 1/2" Pex pipe elbow

• Although the C270 Mount uses the original hinge pin it doesn't have enough friction with the mount itself so it'll just flop around. You can use your own screw/nut to tighten it once you have the camera in the position you want, but I found it best to control the position with the USB cord and securing it with some velcro. See my pictures to get a better idea.
  • Using OctoPrint + GPX Plugin with a Raspberry Pi to record timelapses with the webcam. You can see my OctoPrint build here.

title: Flashforge Creator Pro Adjustable Glass Bed Bracket

description.text:
My previous corner brackets would get loose over time due to the heat of the bed softening the ABS.  Tightening the nut would work temporarily, but then the plastic would heat, and deform again.
This design is made to be more resistant to heat, and not rely on the metal nut to keep it snug against the bed or glass.  To install this, remove the corner nut on the print bed.  Fit the metal nut in the main pin, and join the corner piece and pin back on the metal bolt.  Thread your printed knurled nut on the pin, and adjust to size.  Once you have everything where you want it, tighten the metal nut.
The bolt is compatible with M8 x 1.25
This has been working much better for me, and I haven't needed to adjust the size after at least a dozen prints.

title: Single width walls for perimeter calibration

description.text: There are wonderful calibration sets around. I've just made this one to learn Freecad and to make a fast printing thing to check just perimeter extrusion width (advanced perimeter and extruder tuning).

• Slice the thing (be sure to set perimeters=1 in vertical shells) and open the gcode file.
  • Take note of perimeters extrusion width parameter. In my case it was 0.67, calculated autamatically by Slic3r for a 0.2 layer height with a 0.4mm nozzle.
  • Print.
  • Measure it. Don't include the 2 or 3 bottom layers. Measure the four walls and dismiss the more different one. Average the other three and compare with the parameter in the gcode file.
  • If it's the same, you're done. It should be the same if your extruder steps are correct and you have also measured the filament diameter and have introduced it in the slicing software. If you continue experiencing issues, some people use the extrusion multiplier to adjust this. Extrusion multiplier = Expected value / Measured value. In any case it shouldn't be outside the range 0.9 - 1.1.

description.text: GT2 belt and pulley mod for Mendel90 by nophead

This mod is for the GT2 belt and without an belt twist. -- UPDATE 09.08.2013 ----
Added tensioner to y axis for dibond model You need the following vitamins:
  • 2 GT2 pulley 20 teeth 5mm bore http://www.robotdigg.com/product/9/GT2-Pulley-20-Teeth-5mm-Bore
  • 2 GT2 pulley 20 teeth 8mm bore http://www.robotdigg.com/product/23/GT2-Pulley-20-Teeth-8mm-Bore
  • 663 mm + 903mm GT2 belt
    http://www.robotdigg.com/product/10/Open-Ended-6mm-Width-GT2-Belt
  • 4 M3 4mm grub screws http://www.robotdigg.com/product/17/M34-Grub-Screw-PACK-SET-for-Timing-Pulleys
  • 4 608ZZ ball bearings http://www.robotdigg.com/product/12/608ZZ-Ball-Bearing
  • 1 M8 cap screw x 60mm
  • 1 M8 cap screw x 45mm
  • 2 M8 nyloc nut
  • 2 M8 washer
  • 2 M3 nyloc nut
  • 2 M3 cap screw x 40mm
  • 2 M3 washer
    • INSTRUCTIONS: X-axis mod:
  • Print Mendel90_gt2_x_axis.stl
  • Remove the raft and open the bridge layer in the ball bearing hole with a knife.
  • Open up the bridge layer for screw holes with a drill. (4,5 for M4, 3.3 for M3 screw holes).
  • Press fit the bearings in the x idler holder
  • Put the GT2 pulley with 8mm boring all up on the M8 x 60 cap screw - teeths are closer to the cap. Fix the pulley with the grub screws.
  • Insert the cap screw with pulley into the ball bearings. The pulley is on the top of the printed x idler holder.
  • Fix the cap screw with a washer and a nyloc nut.
  • Check if the pulley revolves easy - otherwise loosen up the nut a little bit.
  • Remove the original x idler M4 cap screw/bearing/washers and the M4 nyloc nut.
  • Remove the belt clamps on the x carriage
  • Replace the stepper motor pulley with the GT2 5mm bore pulley
  • Put the nyloc nut in the GT2 x idler
  • Press fit the GT2 x idler on the original x idler assembly and fix it with the original M4 cap screw
  • Insert the GT2 belt without twist and fix it with the new clamps
  • Adjust the belt tension with the tensioner on the x carriage
    • Y-axis mod:
  • Print Mendel90_gt2_y_axis.stl
  • Open the bridge layers in the ball bearing hole with a knife.
  • Open up the forward and upward looking part of the y idler with a knife and clean up everything.
  • Press fit the bearings in the y idler holder
  • Push the GT2 pulley in the new idler teeth closer to the right
  • Insert the M8 x 45 cap screw and fix it with a M8 washer and nyloc nut.
  • Check if the pulley revolves easy - otherwise loosen up the nut a little bit
  • Insert the two M3 nyloc nuts into the botton
  • Remove the original y idler and put the nyloc nut in the GT2 y idler
  • Remove both y rods and turn the heated bed over
  • Remove both belt clamps and belt
  • Insert the GT2 belt through the GT2 idler without a twist and clamp the GT2 belt to the anchors with the new GT2 clamps. The end of the belt should project enough to have five complete teeth showing.
  • Replace the stepper motor pulley with the GT2 5mm bore pulley
  • Turn over the heated bed and mount on the y rods.
  • Mount the GT2 idler with the original screw but just slightly tighten the screw
  • Put the y axis tensioner over the edge behind the GT2 idler and insert the two M3 x 40 cap screws with two washers into the tensioner and the y idler
  • Adjust tension of the belt and direction of the GT2 idler with the two M3 cap screws
    • No firmware changes needed. I recognized some clack sounds while printing from the GT2 pulleys. These sounds came from the sligtly smaller diameter of the cap screws compared to the pulleys. I fixed this temporary with a little bit of painter tape arount the cap screws where the pulley and the bearings are. Better for now but I'll upgrade to a 8mm rod with two snap rings on both sides. If you just wan't an upgrade to the GT2 belt but with a twist in the belt you need only 2 GT2 pulleys with 5m bore, the GT2 belts and the GT2 belt clamps.

title: Knobs for M3 Brass Standoffs (for FlashForge Creator Glass Clips)

description.text: We've been using the Corner Glass Clips +3mm with our FlashForge Creator Pro printers at TheLab.ms Makerspace for quite a while now, and we're quite pleased with them. We've been using the spare wing nuts that shipping with the printers, and one of those wing nuts eventually stripped an M3 screws. Those wing nuts are only a few threads deep, and that put a lot of stress on the threads on the bolt. These knobs are designed to fit an M3 12mm brass standoff. With 12mm worth of thread, I don't think we'll be stripping any more bolts. I sized the hole to print just barely too tight to fit the standoff. I used my soldering iron to heat up the standoff and press it down into the knob.

comments.text: Very good idea, i think for install you may be better to taper the one side of the hole a bit and then use a long screw and large washer run right through and then tighten the screw to draw the nut inside, then you;ll get perfect depth and perfect center every time... great design though, i think i'll use this for my printer.

They'll definitely fit, but I know those M3 bolts on the corners of the bed are pretty long, and I didn't think to measure them the last time I was at the makerspace.  I'm worried that they're longer than 12mm, and they'll need to poke through the other side of the standoff.  It is OK if they do, though, because I left the other end of the knob wide open.

title: Knights & City Walls for Catan expansion

description.text:
These are some knights for the Settlers of Catan expansion "Cities and Knights". We lost some of our knights to a hungry dog and several of the knights I had seen on thingiverse were too complicated/fragile. These knights are very simple, with a "+" or an "o" for each strength level of the knight, and a small indent on the side for each strength level as well. The city walls are really just simple squares, just like in the real game. 
They're pretty small pieces so you might be able to get away without support, but I printed it with support just in case. I set infill to 30% and printed in black PLA. We colored in the "+" and "o" (different colors) to increase visibility.

comments.text: I made a version that is printer friendly. I made a few changes. 1) The + and 0 are now indents rather than protruding 2) the side groves are now at a 45 degree angle 3) rather than defining the indent on the size for 1-ring, 2-ring, 3-ring... The larger bands now represent the rings of a knight. So the 1-ring knight has no groves (just one solid ring). The 2-ring has one grove to separate the flat-part into two separate rings. The 3-ring knight has 2 groves to separate the flat-part into three separate rings.

Pill Dispenser for up to 20 doses. This tool use NodeMCU(ESP-12) (in C++ mode), that means we use eps8266 as main prosessor.
This cheap little board can run webserver, which is used to setup dose times and internet connection may be used used for time synchronization in future. My application needs no exact times as dosing starts in different time each day. Movement is done with cheap 28BYJ 5VDC step engine and ULN2003 stepper driver, it is accommodated with optical sensor for right position (Carrier wheel have printed special cylinder with spacing). 0.96" I2C 128X64 monochromatic OLED display is used to show immediate data. I use 3* parallel 18650 scrap laptop batteries and TP4056/microusb charger (photo included), it may be replace by another 3.7V+ source (on NodeMCU to Vin). Batteries are not necessary. I did not make it to be "super low consumption device", but it easily works longer then 5 days without charging and display is always on. Control is done by webserver also by one button, and display. Button is any with 12mm and nuts, Recommend easy to press, I already had to replace it. Display show's dose number, sequence number in day and time to next dose. Short button press will move to next dose in daily sequence, mainly because targeted person can start medication in different times as sleeping is irregular.
Button press for 5 seconds will execute full deploy and return to 0 position.
Button press for 30 seconds will execute restart of network configuration. Device is capable of OTA uploads over WIFI. Dose timing is controloed by sequence of minutes (zero means wait for press button)
example: 0,120,1,0,1,120,120,120,120,120
  • fill time is between 16:00-18:00
  • press button around 18:00, pill at position 1 is released
  • 20:00 position 2 released
  • 20:01 position 3 released (another pill before sleep)
  • press button after wake up around 06:00, pill at position 4 is released
  • 6:01 position 5 released
  • 8:00 position 6 released
  • 10:00 position 7 released
  • 12:00 position 8 released
  • 14:00 position 9 released
  • 16:00 position 10 released

Both the large and small rotational inertia top files in this project are of equal mass.  The large inertia file has the majority of its mass out on a large radius away from the axis of rotation, while the small rotational inertia top has it centered around the axis of rotation.
I based the rough size of these tops off of some gyroscopes I had lying around

Project Project: This project is an interactive study of rotational inertia. It is meant to be a fun and engaging activity for student to observe the phenomenon of rotational inertia and its relationship, or lack there of, to linear inertia. Audiences: This project is best suited for high school students. Preparation: This project should be an introductory experiment for the laws of rotational motion. Students should have at least an introduction to laws of motion and rotation. Preferably this experiment should take place after students have learnt about linear inertia and before they learn about rotational inertia. Steps: Students should attempt to spin both the small and large inertia tops and see which one they can get to spin the longest. Mathematics say that the larger inertia top should maintain its rotation more easily. To take it a step further each students spin time for each top can averaged to get a more scientific result. For some additional fun, instructors can also hold a contest to see who can get each top to spin the longest Results: Students should have a developed hands on experience with rotational inertia, learning how it is different from linear inertia, and how mass is not the only factor that determines rotational inertia.
